The '''Anna Wintour Costume Center''' is a wing of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] that houses the collection of the '''Costume Institute'''. The center is named after [[Anna Wintour]], editor-in-chief of ''Vogue'', artistic director of [[Condé Nast]], and chair of the museum's annual [[Met Gala]] (often called the "Met Ball")<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/gallery/2017/may/02/met-gala-2017-avant-garde-looks-on-the-red-carpet-in-pictures|title=Met Gala 2017: avant garde looks on the red carpet – in pictures|last=Marriott|first=Hannah|date=2017-05-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-01-29|last2=Gilbert|first2=Sarah|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> since 1995. It was endowed by [[Jonathan M. Tisch|Lizzie and Jonathan Tisch]].<ref name="Met Names Costume Institute Complex in Honor of Anna Wintour">{{cite web | url=http://www.wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-features/met-names-costume-institute-complex-in-honor-of-anna-wintour-7360586?src=nl/mornReport/20140115 | title=Met Names Costume Institute Complex in Honor of Anna Wintour | publisher=WWD | date=14 January 2014 | accessdate=15 January 2014 | author=Karimzadeh, Marc}}</ref>  As of August 2017, the curator is [[Andrew Bolton (curator)|Andrew Bolton]].<ref name=Trebay>{{cite news|last1=Trebay|first1=Guy|title=At the Met, Andrew Bolton Is the Storyteller in Chief|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/30/fashion/mens-style/at-the-met-andrew-bolton-is-the-storyteller-in-chief.html|accessdate=13 August 2015|publisher=New York Times|date=29 April 2015}}</ref>

The center was formally opened by the [[First Lady of the United States]] [[Michelle Obama]] on May 5, 2014.<ref name="Michelle Obama Cuts the Ribbon at Anna Wintour Costume Center"/> Many famous people, such as [[Sarah Jessica Parker]], [[Diane Von Furstenberg]], [[Tory Burch]], [[Zac Posen]], [[Ralph Lauren]], and [[Donatella Versace]], were at the center's opening.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2014/04/30/michelle-obama-to-open-anna-wintours-met-costume-center/8515179/ |title=Michelle Obama to open Anna Wintour's Met costume center |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=2014-04-30 |accessdate=2014-05-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/michelle-obama-open-met-museum-anna-wintour-costume-center-article-1.1779815 |title=First lady of fashion Anna Wintour gets teary as First Lady Michelle Obama honors her at the Met |publisher=NY Daily News |date=2006-03-17 |accessdate=2014-05-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author =Tiffany Yannetta |url=http://ny.racked.com/archives/2014/05/05/inside_the_costume_institutes_charles_james_exhibition.php |title=Inside the Anna Wintour Costume Center's Charles James Exhibit - Afternoon at the Museum - Racked NY |publisher=Ny.racked.com |date= |accessdate=2014-05-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author = |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/05/05/michelle-obama-cuts-the-ribbon-for-new-anna-wintour-costume-center/ |title=Michelle Obama Cuts the Ribbon for New Anna Wintour Costume Center - Speakeasy - WSJ |publisher=Blogs.wsj.com |date=2012-04-17 |accessdate=2014-05-06}}</ref>

==History==
In 1902, wealthy philanthropists [[Irene Lewisohn|Irene]] and [[Alice Lewisohn]] began to volunteer at the [[Henry Street Settlement]] House in New York, a community center that provided social services and healthcare to immigrant families.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Henry-Street-Settlement|title=Henry Street Settlement|last=|first=|date=|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> Alice, who acted in plays herself, began working as a drama teacher, while Irene devoted herself to dance productions. In 1914, the sisters bought a lot on the corner of Grand and Pitt Streets and donated it to the Settlement for building a new theater. The [[Neighborhood Playhouse School of the Theatre|Neighborhood Playhouse]] opened in 1915. By 1920, the theater employed professional actors, and it was known for its experimental productions and its revue "The Grand Street Follies."<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.nypl.org/mss/2112|title=Neighborhood Playhouse Records|last=|first=|date=|website=New York Public Library Archives & Manuscripts|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> Theater designer [[Aline Bernstein]] served her apprenticeship there from 1915-1924 designing costumes and stage sets.  

The Playhouse closed in 1927, but the company continued to produce plays on Broadway under the management of Helen F. Ingersoll. In 1928, with Rita Wallach Morganthau, the Lewisohns established the [[Neighborhood Playhouse School of the Theatre]] at East 54th Street, where it became an actor training school and students were offered a two-year program formal drama and dance training to become professionals.<ref name=":0" /> [[File:Robe à la française 1740s.jpg|thumb|left|Robe à la française 1740s, as seen in one of the exhibits at the Costume Institute]]During their years of running the school theatre and producing plays, a body of knowledge was formed about acting, theater production, and costume, set and stage design. In 1937, Irene Lewisohn opened a home for this library, the Museum of Costume Art, on Fifth Avenue. Aline Bernstein served as the first President and Polaire Weissman as its first Executive Director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libmma.org/digital_files/archives/Costume_Institute_records_b18646104.pdf|title=Costume Institute Records, 1937-2008|last=|first=|date=|website=Metropolitan Museum of Art Archives|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> In 1946 the museum moved to the first floor of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], becoming The Costume Institute. In 1959, it became a curatorial department in the museum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/about-the-met/curatorial-departments/the-costume-institute|title=The Costume Institute|last=|first=|date=|website=www.metmuseum.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref> The Met is now home to the Irene Lewisohn Costume Reference Library.

Since 1946, with help from the fashion publicist [[Eleanor Lambert]], the institute has hosted the annual [[Met Gala]], to raise money for operating expenses.<ref name=NYT/>

In 2008, the American Costume Collection of the [[Brooklyn Museum]] merged into the Costume Institute, a cost-saving scheme coming after years of close collaboration between the two organizations. The collection of the Brooklyn museum is older, having been formed from private donations by former New York high society personalities, beginning with the donation in 1903 of an 1892 cream crepe dress worn by Kate Mallory Williams at her graduation from Brooklyn Heights Seminary.<ref name=NYT>[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/16/arts/design/16muse.html Brooklyn Museum’s Costume Treasures Going to the Met], New York Times article in December 2008</ref> Prior to the move, 23,500 objects from the Brooklyn collection were digitized and these images are now shared by both organizations.<ref name=Artstor>[http://www.artstor.org/what-is-artstor/w-html/col-brooklyn-costume.shtml Collection of the Brooklyn Museum costumes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140430151133/http://www.artstor.org/what-is-artstor/w-html/col-brooklyn-costume.shtml |date=2014-04-30 }} on Artstor</ref> At the time of the merger, the Met costume collection consisted of 31,000 objects from the 17th-century onwards.<ref name=Artstor/> The opening exhibition in 2014 featured work by British-born designer [[Charles James (designer)|Charles James]], an important figure in New York fashion of the 1940s and 1950s and whose work is in the Brooklyn collection.
<ref name="Michelle Obama Cuts the Ribbon at Anna Wintour Costume Center">{{cite web | url=http://www.wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-features/michelle-obama-cuts-the-ribbon-at-anna-wintour-costume-center-7667268?src=nl/mornReport/20140506 | title=Michelle Obama Cuts the Ribbon at Anna Wintour Costume Center | publisher=WWD | date=5 May 2014 | accessdate=7 May 2014 | author=Karimzadeh,  Marc}}</ref>

On September 8, 2015, it was announced that [[Harold Koda]] would be stepping down from his position as Curator in Charge of the Costume Institute. Andrew Bolton, who had joined the Costume Institute in 2002 as associate curator and was made curator in 2006, was announced as his replacement.<ref name="metmuseum.org">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/press/news/2015/harold-koda-retirement|title=Harold Koda to Step Down After Leading Met Museum’s Costume Institute for 15 Years; Andrew Bolton to Become Curator In Charge of the Department|last=|first=|date=8 September 2015|website=The Met|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315012834/http://www.metmuseum.org/press/news/2015/harold-koda-retirement|archive-date=15 March 2017|dead-url=|access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref>

In May 2017, the Costume Institute featured an exhibition featuring the works of [[Rei Kawakubo]]/[[Comme des Garçons]]. The exhibit was the Costume Institute's first exhibition focusing on a living designer since [[Yves Saint Laurent (designer)|Yves Saint Laurent]] in 1983.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/met-gala-2017-theme-rei-kawakubo-comme-des-garcons|title=The 2017 Met Gala Theme Will Be Comme des Garçons’s Rei Kawakubo|website=Vogue|language=en|access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref>

